US-Asian groups complained to the enrollment discrimination of 3 Ivy Schools, including Yale-Xinhua News Agency, Xinhua News Agency, Washington, May 23 (Reporter Xu Jianmei) More than 130 Asian groups in the United States submitted a complaint to the US Ministry of Education and the Ministry of Justice on the 23rd to protest 3	 The Ivy League School -Yale University, Brown University, and Datmouth College discriminated against Asian applicants during the enrollment process.	 The Asian Education Alliance, which led the appeal, held a press conference in Washington on the same day.	 The chairman of the group said at the press conference that in the past 10 years, the number of Asian applicants who meet the admission conditions of famous American schools has doubled, but among these three famous American universities, Asians have basically maintained at the same level.	 Many studies have shown that during the so -called "comprehensive consideration" enrollment process, these universities "long -term sustainability and systematic discrimination against Asian applications." Zhao Yukong said that research by scholars such as Sanders in 2014 showed that in these three universities, the number of Asians in all ethnic groups was the lowest in all the applicants.	 Data from the Ministry of Education of the United States also show that among all Ivy League schools, the admission ratio of Bronn University and Dartmouth College has the lowest proportion of Asian students.	 For more than 20 years.	 Zhao Yukong told Xinhua News Agency reporters that after they expected to submit the complaint, the Ministry of Education and the Ministry of Justice of the United States and the Ministry of Justice could conduct investigations and took measures to prevent these universities from continuing to discriminate against Asians in enrollment.	 They also expect that colleges and universities can take the initiative to pay attention to this issue and change their enrollment policies for Asians.	 At present, the three universities that have been complained have not responded. The Asian Education Alliance was established in 2015. At that time, the Harvard University enrollment discrimination was complained, but the Ministry of Education of the United States did not accept procedures.	 In addition to the Chinese groups participating in the appeal, it also includes the US Indian, Korean, Japanese, and Pakistan educational groups.
